                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d479">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3619: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Crane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-11-17T18:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 17, 1920—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>386. Japanese Minister officially informed Foreign Office that Hsu had escaped
                    from the Japanese Legation night of 14th. Unconfirmed rumors state that [he] has
                    fled to Mongolia. Another theory from Chinese sources is that Hsu is going to
                    Shanghai to intrigue with Canton, forming [Anfuite] provincial coalition against
                    Peking. Reported also Nishihara in Shanghai negotiating Japanese loan to
                    South.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
